Grammar on the fly
Incant is homoiconic: a grammar rule is a field, and a field is a first-class object. grammarOnTheFly is a short file that demonstrates what that means in practice — a live grammar mutation, a self-capture, and a file write, all from running incant code.
Its crux is three lines:
DelimText isRule '('- dtext^}=delimiter;
DatA += DelimText;
guard(DatA);
DelimText is a rule that captures everything between ( and a closing delimiter string. += appends it as a live alternative to DatA, one of incant's 32 bootstrap rules. guard(DatA) clears the cached guard set so the parser re-derives it after seeing DelimText for the first time.
On the very next definition, incant parses a 3654-byte comment block through the alternative that did not exist when the session began. No recompile, no restart, no grammar file rewrite. The parser's own rule table is a live data structure, reachable and writable from incant code. The locomotive changes while the train stays on schedule.
These three lines are wrapped in a single utility action:
changeDatA();
Users need not know or care what it does under the hood — but it is doing exactly this. The DatA rule mutation is not a demonstration artifact; it is load-bearing. The (…#) delimited literals that appear in the comment block it reads — containing commas, periods, and embedded parentheses — are parsed through the DatA alternative that changeDatA grafts in.
The demonstration goes one step further. grammarOnTheFly uses printTO to feed the captured comment into a buffer field, then writes it to disk using a modifiable operator writable at runtime:
modedOP operateMethod=setFileOp;         // rebinds modedOP's function pointer to setFileOp,
                                         // a wrapper method that works as an incant operator
doc modedOP "incant/grammarOnTheFly.out"; // fires setFileOp: doc is target, path is argument
closeFile(doc);
grammarOnTheFly was written not because writing a file is hard, and neither is adding a comment to one. It was written to show incant can capture its own documentation through a grammar rule that didn't exist at startup, then write it to disk.
stop() exits and leaves the original bootstrap grammar in place so the graft does not persist beyond the file. The proof is not a toy string — it is a lengthy comment block captured through the rule that wasn't there when incant started.

modedOP — a writable operator
Incant operators are fields. Like any field, the method an operator dispatches to is an attribute — which means it can be set. modedOP is an ordinary infix operator in the Operators registry whose method slot (operateMethod) is designed to be re-pointed. It is incant's proof of concept for a runtime-rebindable operator.
In its current form, modedOP is pre-bound at startup to setFileOp, a shim that attaches a buffer field to a file path:
doc modedOP "/path/to/output.out";
Left operand is the target (a buffer field); right operand is the path. After this fires, writing to doc and calling closeFile(doc) lands the content on disk. The working example is in incant/grammarOnTheFly:
doc buffer;                               // doc is a buffer field
...                                       // fill doc with content
doc modedOP "incant/grammarOnTheFly.out"; // attach to file
closeFile(doc);                           // flush and close
The "moded" in the name points at what isn't built yet: true runtime rebinding from incant code, so that modedOP can be re-pointed at a different method mid-session without a recompile. The pre-binding through operateMethod=setFileOp in setup establishes the pattern; the open task is making that same binding writable from a live incant statement via modedOP.boundTo. Note that = will not do it — setContent ignores the gOp slot by design — so rebinding has to route through operateMethod and its underlying setOperat call.
When boundTo is implemented, modedOP becomes a general-purpose operator slot: name it once, re-point it as needed, and any code using the symbol picks up the new behavior. The file-write use case is the first concrete application; the mechanism is the point.
